{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*1799\u20131801 [[John Hunter (physician)|John Hunter]] <ref name = rRCP/>\n*1796\u20131798 [[Matthew Baillie]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cgi-bin/vcdf/detail?coll_id=7094&inst_id=8&nv1=search&nv2= |title=AIM25 collection description |publisher=Aim25.ac.uk |accessdate=2011-09-19}}</ref>\n*1795 [[John Latham (physician)|John Latham]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/5073 |title=Munks Roll Details for John Latham |publisher=Munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk |accessdate=2011-09-19}}</ref>\n*1793 [[John Ash (physician)|John Ash]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cgi-bin/vcdf/detail?coll_id=11928&inst_id=18&nv1=search&nv2= |title=AIM25 collection description |publisher=Aim25.ac.uk |accessdate=2011-09-19}}</ref>\n*1791 James Robertson Barclay  <ref>{{cite book|title = The Roll of the Royal College of Physicians of London, Volume 2|publisher= Royal College of Physicians|volume = 2|page= 319}}</ref>\n*1788\u20131790 Francis Riollay <ref name = rRCP/>\n*1787 [[George Fordyce]]<ref>{{cite journal |last=Coley |first=N.G. |title=George Fordyce M.D., F.R.S. (1736\u20131802): physician-chemist and eccentric |journal=Notes and Records of the Royal Society of London |volume=55 |issue=3 |pages=395\u2013409 |date=September 2001 |pmid=11713784 |doi=10.1098/rsnr.2001.0154}}</ref>\n*1784-1786 [[Thomas Heald]]<ref name=\"healds.org.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.healds.org.uk/alumni.html |title=Heald University Alumni and Clergy, UK |publisher=Healds.org.uk |accessdate=2011-09-19}}</ref>\n*1781 Francis Milman  <ref>{{cite book|title = The Roll of the Royal College of Physicians of London, Volume 2|publisher= Royal College of Physicians|volume = 2|page= 270}}</ref> An Inquiry into the Source from whence the Symptoms of the Scurvy and of Putrid Fevers arise <ref name = rRCP/>\n*1774\u20131775 [[Donald Monro (physician)|Donald Monro]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BtPlGsKKaa8C&pg=PA183&lpg=PA183&dq=croonian+1753#v=onepage&q=croonian%201753&f=false |title=Dictionary of National Biography |date=7 May 2007 |accessdate=2011-09-19|isbn=9781402170652 |last1=Lee |first1=Sidney }}</ref>\n*1770 [[Thomas Heald]]<ref name=\"healds.org.uk\"/>\n*1763 Richard Brocklesby <ref>{{cite book|title = The Roll of the Royal College of Physicians of London, Volume 2|publisher= Royal College of Physicians|volume = 2|page= 175}}</ref>\n*1760 [[William Heberden the elder|William Heberden]]<ref>{{cite journal |last=Jay |first=V. |title=The legacy of William Heberden |journal=Archives of Pathology & Laboratory Medicine |volume=124 |issue=12 |pages=1750\u20131751 |date=December 2000 |pmid=11100049 |url=https://www.archivesofpathology.org/doi/full/10.1043/0003-9985%282000%29124%3C1751%3ATLOWH%3E2.0.CO%3B2\n|doi=10.1043/0003-9985(2000)124<1751:TLOWH>2.0.CO;2|doi-broken-date=2020-01-07 }}</ref>\n*1758\u20131759 [[Thomas Lawrence (physician)|Thomas Lawrence]]<ref name = rRCP/>\n*1756 [[Mark Akenside]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/50 |title=Munks Roll Details for Mark Akenside |publisher=Munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk |accessdate=2011-09-19}}</ref>\n*1749\u20131755 Thomas Lawrence, ''De natura musculorum''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cats/8/7198.htm |title=AIM25 text-only browsing: Royal College of Physicians: Lawrence, Thomas (1711\u20131783) |publisher=Aim25.ac.uk |accessdate=2011-09-19}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=50em}}\n\n{{RoySoc}}\n\n[[Category:Royal Society lecture series]]\n[[Category:Royal College of Physicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox award\n| caption = The lecture is named after [[William Croone]] (1633\u20131684), portrait painted by [[Mary Beale]] in 1680\n| name = Croonian Medal and Lecture\n| image = File:William Croone 1680.jpg\n| location = [[London]]\n| website =  {{URL|https://royalsociety.org/grants-schemes-awards/awards/croonian-lecture/}} \n}}\nThe '''Croonian Lectures''' are prestigious lectureships given at the invitation of the [[Royal Society]] and the [[Royal College of Physicians]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://royalsociety.org/awards/croonian-lecture/| title= Croonian Lecture|publisher= Royal Society|accessdate = 23 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.rcplondon.ac.uk/sites/default/files/croonian_factsheet.pdf|title = Croonian Lectures (Sadleir Trust)|publisher = Royal College of Physicians|accessdate = 23 December 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140408211843/http://www.rcplondon.ac.uk/sites/default/files/croonian_factsheet.pdf|archivedate = 8 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nAmong the papers of [[William Croone]] at his death in 1684, was a plan to endow one lectureship at both the [[Royal Society]] and the [[Royal College of Physicians]]. His wife provided the bequest in 1701 specifying that it was \"for the support of a lecture and illustrative experiment for the advancement of natural knowledge on local motion, or (conditionally) of such other subjects as, in the opinion of the President for the time being, should be most useful in promoting the objects for which the Royal Society was instituted\". One lecture was to be delivered by a Fellow to the Royal College of Physicians and the other, on the nature and laws of muscular motion to be delivered before the Royal Society. The Royal Society lecture series began in 1738 and that of the Royal College of Physicians in 1749.<ref name = rRCP>{{cite book| title = The roll of the Royal College of Physicians of London, comprising biographical sketches of all the eminent physicians whose names are recorded in the Annals .. (Volume 3)|publisher= Royal College of Physicians|accessdate = }} ebook</ref>\n\nCroone became an original Fellow of the Royal Society in May 1663.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://royalsociety.org/uploadedFiles/Royal_Society_Content/about-us/fellowship/Fellows1660-2007.pdf|title=Lists of Royal Society Fellows 1660\u20132007|publisher=The Royal Society|accessdate=12 August 2010|location=London}}</ref> He also became a [https://history.rcplondon.ac.uk/inspiring-physicians/william-croone Fellow] of the [[Royal College of Physicians|College of Physicians]] on 29 July 1675. He was appointed lecturer on anatomy at Surgeons' hall in 1670 and pursued research in several important subjects of his day, including respiration, muscular motion, and generation.\n\n== List of lecturers (Royal Society \u2013 for RCP lecturers see below)==\nSource: [https://royalsociety.org/grants-schemes-awards/awards/croonian-lecture/ Royal Society]\n\n=== 21st century ===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* 2020 [[Edward Boyden]], ''for his inventions that expand our understanding of the brain and allow therapeutic development including the co-invention of optogenetics, a technology that has revolutionised neurobiology''\n* 2019 Dame [[Kay Davies]], ''for her achievements in developing a prenatal test for Duchenne muscular dystrophy and her work on characterising dystrophin related proteins ''<ref> {{cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/grants-schemes-awards/awards/croonian-lecture/|title=Croonian Medal and Lecture winner 2019|publisher= Royal Society|accessdate= 6 August 2018}} </ref>\n* 2018 [[Jennifer Doudna]], ''Re-writing the Code of Life: CRISPR Systems and Applications of Gene Editing'' <ref> {{cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/science-events-and-lectures/2018/05/croonian-prize-lecture/|title=Re-writing the Code of Life: CRISPR Systems and Applications of Gene Editing |publisher= Royal Society|accessdate= 6 August 2018}} </ref>\n* 2017 [[Jonathan Ashmore|Jonathan Felix Ashmore]], ''for his significant contributions to the field of sensory neuroscience, shaping our current understanding of inner ear physiology'' <ref>{{cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/grants-schemes-awards/awards/croonian-lecture/|title= Croonian Medal and Lecture-Croonian Medallist 2017|publisher= Royal Society|accessdate= 14 September 2016}}</ref>\n* 2016 [[Enrico Coen]], ''for his work resulting in a new theoretical and experimental foundation for understanding how the shapes of biological structures arise through development and evolution''\n* 2015 [[Nicholas Barry Davies]], ''for his work on the co-evolved responses of brood parasitic cuckoos and their hosts''\n* 2014 [[Brigid Hogan]], ''for pioneering contributions that have transformed understanding of cell specification, organogenesis and morphogenesis in mammalian development'' <ref name=\"Croonian Lecture\">{{cite web|url = http://royalsociety.org/awards/croonian-lecture/|title= Croonian Lecture|publisher= Royal Society|accessdate = 2013-09-12}}</ref>\n* 2013 [[Frances Ashcroft]], ''From bench to bedside: KATP channels and neonatal diabetes'' <ref name=\"Croonian Lecture\"/>\n* 2012 [[Timothy Bliss|Tim Bliss]], ''The Mechanics of Memory'' <ref>{{cite web| url = http://royalsociety.org/events/2012/memory/|title= The mechanics of memory| publisher= The Royal Society|accessdate = 2012-09-07}}</ref>\n* 2011 [[R. John Ellis|John Ellis]],''Molecular chaperones: how cells stop proteins from misbehaving''\n* 2010 [[Alec Jeffries]], ''Genetic fingerprinting and beyond''\n* 2009 [[Linda Partridge]], ''The New Biology of Ageing''\n* 2008 [[John Pickett (biologist)|John Pickett]], ''Plant and Animal Communication''<ref>{{cite web |title=Plant and animal communication |url=http://royalsociety.org/Event.aspx?id=2082 |year=2009 |publisher=Royal Society}}</ref>\n* 2007 [[Aaron Klug]], ''Engineered zinc finger proteins (ZFPs) for the regulation of gene expression''\n* 2006 [[Iain Campbell (academic)|Iain Campbell]], ''Structure and the living cell''<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1098/rstb.2006.1960 |pmc=1955230 |pmid=17255009 |title=The Croonian lecture 2006 Structure of the living cell |year=2008 |last1=Campbell |first1=Iain D. |journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences |volum